
✅ Azure Spring Boot App Deployment via GitHub Actions – Structured Notes:-

🔹 Step 1: Azure Setup (Resource Group & Web App)
           1. Login to Azure Portal → https://portal.azure.com
           2. Go to App Services → Click Create → Choose:
           3. Resource Group Name: e.g., securityDev20250517
           4. App Name: e.g., dev-security
              ⮕ This becomes part of the public API URL: https://dev-security-xxxx.azurewebsites.net
           5. Runtime Stack: Java 17
           6. OS: Linux
           7. Pricing Tier: Free (F1)

🔹 Step 2: Link GitHub to Azure App Service
           1. Go to Deployment Center in the created App Service
           2. Source: Select GitHub
           3. Organization: e.g., ritkrs
           4. Repository: security_16052025
           5. Branch: dev
           6. Workflow option: Add a workflow file
           7. Authentication: Use User-assigned identity (auto-managed)

 🔄 This step will auto-create a .yml workflow file in GitHub → .github/workflows/

 🤔 .yml file kyu banta hai? Aur manually kyun banaya?

 🔹 .yml kya hota hai?
    1. Ye ek GitHub Actions ka workflow file hota hai.
    2. Jab bhi aap GitHub repo me push karte ho, ye file batata hai ki kya-kya kaam karna hai.
       1. Jaise: Build karna, test karna, deploy karna.

 🔹 Automatically kab banta hai?
    1. Jab aap Azure portal ke Deployment Center se GitHub link karte ho,
    2. Aur option select karte ho:
       ✅ “Add a workflow file”
    3. Tab Azure khud .yml file create kar deta hai repo ke andar:
       .github/workflows/dev-dev-security.yml

  🔹 Hume manually kyun banana/edit karna pada?
     1. Azure ne file to banaya tha, lekin assume kar liya ki pom.xml project root me hai.
     2. Lekin tumhare project ka actual path tha:
         /security_16052025/security/pom.xml
     3. Isiliye .yml me hume ye line add karni padi:
        working-directory: ./security


  🔹 Step 3: GitHub Actions Build + Deploy Flow (Hinglish Notes)
             1. Whenever you commit or push to dev branch:
             2. Workflow will trigger:
                1. Build the project using mvn clean install
                2. Package the JAR
                3. Deploy to Azure App Service


                ✅ Successful deploy will expose the endpoint on:
                   https://<app-name>.azurewebsites.net/<your-controller-mapping>
                   E.g:-  https://dev-security-xxxxx.centralindia-01.azurewebsites.net/test/api


                   🎉 Deployment Confirmation
                      1. Verify API in Postman or browser
                      2. Status: ✅ 200 Ok
                      3.  Response: Your controller response (e.g., "Details")

















